Every fake article should include some "tell". tells are indications that this can't be true. tells should be fairly obvious to a child.

some categories of tells:
 - something impossible
 - something happening at the wrong time (too early / too late / wrong season / wrong month / etc)
 - something happening in the wrong place (a city in the wrong country / location that wouldn't be suitable / etc)
 - two events happening at a wrong relative time (college too soon after birth / war happening before the inciting incident / etc)
 - something so big or consequential that it would be known to all 
 - something incredibly implausible (especially if humorous)
 - something self contradictory / oxymoron / paradox
 - something that violates well known rules / science

remember, being merely improbable is not enough. Example: a basoonist could win a pulitzer prize, but they couldn't win the prize for a melody they composed. Tells should not rely on external knowledge that is not common. For example, detecting the fake should not require the player to know that FDR died shortly before the end of WWII, but it's fine to assume people know he wasn't alive in the 80s.

